SIMPLE: harness
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Harness
<hw>Har"ness</hw> <pr>(-n⟦ecr⟧s)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>harneis</ets>, <ets>harnes</ets>, OF. <ets>harneis</ets>, F.
<ets>harnais</ets>, <ets>harnois</ets>; of Celtic origin; cf. Armor.
<ets>harnez</ets> old iron, armor, W. <ets>haiarn</ets> iron, Armor.
<ets>houarn</ets>, Ir. <ets>iarann</ets>, Gael. <ets>iarunn</ets>. Cf.
<er>Iron</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Originally, the complete dress,
especially in a military sense, of a man or a horse; hence, in general,
armor.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>At least we'll die with <qex>harness</qex> on our back.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The equipment of a draught or carriage horse, for
drawing a wagon, coach, chaise, etc.; gear; tackling.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>The part of a loom comprising the heddles, with
their means of support and motion, by which the threads of the warp are
alternately raised and depressed for the passage of the
shuttle.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To die in harness</b></col>, <cd>to die with armor on;
hence, colloquially, to die while actively engaged in work or
duty.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Harness</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Harness
<hw>Har"ness</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Harnessed</conjf> <pr>(-n⟦ecr⟧st)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Harnessing</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE.
<ets>harneisen</ets>; cf. F. <ets>harnacher</ets>, OF.
<ets>harneschier</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To dress in armor; to
equip with armor for war, as a horseman; to array.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Harnessed</qex> in rugged steel.</q>
<rj><qau>Rowe.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A gay dagger,⟦br⟧
<qex>Harnessed</qex> well and sharp as point of spear.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Fig.: To equip or furnish for defense.</def> <au>Dr.
H. More.</au>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To make ready for draught; to equip with harness, as
a horse. Also used figuratively.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Harnessed</qex> to some regular profession.</q> <rj><qau>J.
C. Shairp.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Harnessed antelope</b></col>. <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <cd>See
<er>Guib</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Harnessed moth</b></col>
<fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>an American bombycid moth (<spn>Arctia
phalerata</spn> of Harris), having, on the fore wings, stripes and bands
of buff on a black ground.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Harness cask</ent>⟦br⟧
